- in css, colors are represented by named colors and number combinations

- here you can find all the colors represented by hexadecimal numbers
--> https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/color_value

- rgb colors are represented by using decimal numbers         -->          color: rgb(23, 45, 23);
- rgb and hex colors contain the same colors. With rgb each number has a number 0-255 
- first represents the amount of red, the second green and the last one blue

- hsl means hue, saturation, lighteness        -->   color: hsl(120, 60%, 70%);
- hue means the angle on the color wheel, saturaty represents the purity and lightness darkness

-->  color: hsla(34, 100%, 50%, 0.1);        //you  can change the opacity 
--> the last value is the alpha. (1 is opaque, 0 is transparent)
- you can add the opacity to a rgb number and hx number aswell, with hex the opacity goes from 00 to FF
- you can also use color: transparent
                                                                            


- - -- --  - - - - - - -- - - - - --  -  - - - -  - -- -  -- - - - - - - - - -- -- - - - - -- - -- -  - - -- - - - -- - - - - - - 


- css has different kind of fonts, some are supported on most web sites
- Here you can find all the fonts available for css   -->    https://www.cssfontstack.com/

h1 {                                                      //this is a font stack, first the browser will try to use caslon
  font-family: Caslon, Georgia, 'Times New Roman';        //if it is not supported by the browser, then georgia and then times new roman
}

- there are serif and sans-serif fonts. Serif fonts have extra details on the main strokes of the letters
- you can add serif or sans-serif as keywords at tthe end of the stack. In case none of the fonts are available, some serif or else font will be used to display the content


-   font-weight: bold; 
--> here you can control how thin or bold the text appears. Other values are normal, bolder and lighter.
--> you can also use numerical values from 1 to 1000(700=bold), but this feature is not available for all fonts.


- font-style: italic;                 --> here the font has been changed to italics. The default value for font-style is normal. 
- text-transform: uppercase;          --> you can change the text either to uppercase or lowercase.
- letter-spacing: 2px;                --> each character will be 2 pixels apart from each other, you can use px or em
- word-spacing: 0.3em;                --> determines the space between words, em is recommended for words, but you can also use pixels
- line-height: 1.4;                   --> changes the height between the lines, values can be 1.4, 5%, em or px


- remember text_align above!!
- you can link free fonts from google etc. to your file using the <link> element
- another possibility is to use bought fonts that you link to the stylesheet using a relative path. (You need to host the files alongside your website)


- you can choose a free font from google fonts, for example and link it to your stylsheet with the <link> (add it to your <head>)
-->  <link href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Roboto:wght@100&display=swap" rel="stylesheet">
--> after you need to specify the selected font in the stylesheet, like done above


- using @font-face you first need to download the wanted font to your computer. WOFF2 is the most progressive file type.

@font-face {
  font-family: 'MyParagraphFont';                                //custom font name 
  src: url('fonts/Roboto.woff2') format('woff2'),                // fonts linked through a relative link
       url('fonts/Roboto.woff') format('woff'),
       url('fonts/Roboto.ttf') format('truetype');
}
--> after linking the fonts, you need to specify them by using: font-family like stated before
